Question 1

Question:
Write a Java program to show the application of the super keyword to access a superclass data member.

Program:

class Parent {
    int x = 10;
}

class Child extends Parent {
    int x = 20;

    void display() {
        System.out.println("Parent x = " + super.x);
        System.out.println("Child x = " + x);
    }

    public static void main(String args[]) {
        Child obj = new Child();
        obj.display();
    }
}


Output:

Parent x = 10
Child x = 20


Explanation:
The super keyword is used to access the parent class variable when both parent and child have variables with the same name.

Question 2

Question:
Write a Java program to show the application of the super keyword to access a superclass constructor.

Program:

class Parent {
    Parent() {
        System.out.println("Parent class constructor");
    }
}

class Child extends Parent {
    Child() {
        super();
        System.out.println("Child class constructor");
    }

    public static void main(String args[]) {
        Child obj = new Child();
    }
}


Output:

Parent class constructor
Child class constructor


Explanation:
The super() call is used to invoke the parent class constructor.

Question 3

Question:
Define a class Dimension. Create two subclasses Rectangle and Triangle.
Using method overriding, find the area of Rectangle and Triangle.

Program:

class Dimension {
    int a, b;

    Dimension(int x, int y) {
        a = x;
        b = y;
    }

    void area() {
        System.out.println("Area not defined");
    }
}

class Rectangle extends Dimension {

    Rectangle(int l, int b) {
        super(l, b);
    }

    void area() {
        System.out.println("Area of Rectangle = " + (a * b));
    }
}

class Triangle extends Dimension {

    Triangle(int base, int height) {
        super(base, height);
    }

    void area() {
        System.out.println("Area of Triangle = " + (0.5 * a * b));
    }
}

class Main {
    public static void main(String args[]) {
        Rectangle r = new Rectangle(5, 4);
        Triangle t = new Triangle(6, 3);

        r.area();
        t.area();
    }
}


Output:

Area of Rectangle = 20
Area of Triangle = 9.0


Explanation:
Method overriding allows a subclass to provide its own implementation of a method defined in the parent class.
